17 f. destrictus ensis, etc.: the reference is to the familiar story of the sword ofDamocles, told by Cic. Tnsc. 5, 61. It here typifies the uneasy conscience and ever-pres- ent fear of death that threaten the wicked3 hence impia cervice. —cuiz equivalent to ei cml—Siculae: the Sicilians were proverbially luxu- rious, and the adjective is especially appropriate in connection with the reference to Damocles. Note that dapes is by its position contrasted with impia—⁴ No rich banquets can offset the tyrant's wickedness.'
